              Additional Information/Clarification:

A  few  customers have been confused over the "front" and  "back"
models.  Here are a few examples:

Case 1:
______________________________ Edge of Motherboard
=======================1   72 Pin SIMM Banks
=======================0
++++++++++++++++3          30 Pin SIMM Banks
++++++++++++++++2
++++++++++++++++1
++++++++++++++++0

Assuming  Chip  Direction is this way (away from the  motherboard
edge).
\/   \/    \/

You need the REAR model here.  The SIMM Saver would be placed  in
the  first  72 pin SIMM slot (#0), temporarily blocking  the  2nd
(#1)  72 pin SIMM slot.  When you add another 72 pin SIMM in  the
future,  simply move the SIMM Saver to the second  72  pin  slot,
allowing space for the new 72 pin SIMM in the first 72 pin slot.

Case 2:
_______________________________ Edge of Motherboard
+++++++++++++++3
+++++++++++++++2
+++++++++++++++1
+++++++++++++++0
======================1
======================0       72 Pin SIMMS

Assuming  Chip  Direction is this way (away from the  motherboard
edge).
\/   \/    \/

You  would  need the FRONT model here, installed  into  slot  #0,
facing toward your expansion cards.  The second 72 pin SIMM  slot
(#1) would still be free.

Case 3:
_______________________________ Edge of Motherboard
======================3
======================2
======================1
======================0       72 Pin SIMMS

Assuming  Chip  Direction is this way (away from the  motherboard
edge).
\/   \/    \/

You  can  use  EITHER the front or back model,  the  front  model
should  be  installed in the first SIMM bank (#0), and  the  rear
model,  in either slot #1.  As you add SIMMS, you would move  the
rear  model SIMM Saver towards the motherboard edge to allow  for
clearance.  For example, installing a 72 pin SIMM with  two  SIMM
Savers  would mean one 72 pin SIMM in slot #1, with a SIMM  Saver
in #0 and #2.
     Filling all the slots up would mean a SIMM Saver in slots #0
and #3, with 72 pins memory occupying slots #1 and #2.

If  your  chip  directions are opposite, don't worry.   THE  MAIN
THING IS TO DETERMINE IS WHICH ORIENTATION WILL PROVIDE THE  MOST
CLEARANCE FOR THE SIMM SAVER.  Here are some hints:

1.     Figure  out which direction will avoid clearance  problems
     with any CPUs, expansion cards, or power cords.

2.     Check  to see which direction will not cause intereference
     with  the installed SIMMS.  Check to see which side  the  30
     pin SIMMS will be facing once installed in the 30 pin slots.
     This is your "front side".

       Once  you've  determined your "front" side, check  to  see
whether  or not the SIMM Saver SIMMS will cause intereference  on
this side.  If yes, then you need the "back" model.


